7373005780460539168.video_description: #stitch with rynnstar if you’ve ever wondered just how big the US is compared to Europe — here you go! #europevsusa #usa #europeans #geography #funfacts #LearnOnTikTok #greenscreen
7373005780460539168.voice_to_text: Thing that Europeans really can't wrap their heads around is how fucking big this country. She is 100% correct. I've had to explain to my friends in Europe so many times just how big the United States is, and I wanna show you the example that I always use. So if you wanted to drive from Seattle to New York City, it would be 2,851 miles and take 43 hours. So let's say you start in Paris. How far would that same drive get you? Maybe Moscow? Nope, this is only 1,763 miles. Not even close. So Paris to Moscow only gets you from Seattle to just over the border in Wisconsin. You wouldn't even make it to Chicago with that distance. And drum roll Seattle to New York is the equivalent of driving from Paris to northern Iraq. And not only are you not in Europe anymore, you're in Asia, but you would to drive through Germany, Austria, Serbia, Bulgaria, Hungary, and Turkey. Not in that order though. Not to mention that is just the continental US. This is the size of Alaska comparatively. And this is Alaska on Europe. So yeah, the United States is huge.

7372288056851729706.voice_to_text: I said I want something big I want something that says I'm here Beyonce hi my name is Judy I'm a lactation consultant and let me tell you why it is actually so normal for your areolas to get darker and larger during pregnancy so it's likely due to all the hormone changes that you're going through and your body actually has an increase in melanin which causes your areolas to get darker and possibly other areas of your body and your skin could get darker as well some scientists also believe that darker and larger areolas can actually help your baby find and locate where to latch onto especially since their vision isn't fully developed yet at birth your areolas may return to its original size and color although the timing of when that will happen will vary could be anywhere from a few weeks to a few months postpartum and for some individuals it might just stay that way but isn't the human body such a crazy and beautiful thing

7368638779055213854.voice_to_text: absolute fact pirates are actually a lot more orderly and meticulous when attacking a ship than we might think hello everyone my name is Doctor Rebecca Simon and I'm historian of the golden age of piracy and give Pat a follow his videos are brilliant and this one is just top tier he's comparing and contrasting how pirates are depicted in films versus real life in terms of how they attack a ship in films pirates are often like our our matey kill kill kill but in real life it was actually pretty orderly you wanted to get in and out as fast as you can because pirates wanted to survive they didn't want any members of their crew to get killed so what they would often do would be using some sort of scare tactics such as Samuel Bellamy who he and his crew would charge naked on the ships or Blackbeard putting fuses in his beard but the reality is they pirates wanted to talk to the other captain they wanted to look at the manifest they wanted to look at the logs they wanted to see what goods they had so that way they could take what they needed to replenish their own ship and also sell you can read more about these pirate tactics in my book Pirates Code Laws and Life Aboard Ship

7367897453615516970.voice_to_text: So I was addicted to nasal spray for many, many years, and I haven't used it ever since. I stopped. I hate to tell you guys this, but I relapsed on nasal spray this weekend. I was at Coachella in the desert, and the desert sand was in my nose, and I was so congested. And it's like, nasal spray is one of those things. I'm like, oh, I know I can fix this. Like, nasal spray would fix this. And I hate a stuffy nose. And so I just. I got it and it worked, and it was amazing, and I was like, ah! And I felt so much better. But now I used it, so I used it for three days in a row, which is exactly what you're not supposed to do. Like, so I can't use it another day. If you. If you hit that four day Mark, like, you are gonna start to get addicted to it. So let's break this down for a second. Not all needle sprays are created equally. There are nasal saline sprays, which just wash out your nasal passages. There are nasal antihistamine sprays, which can be used as needed. And it's similar to oral antihistamines, is just in a nasal formulation. There are nasal steroids sprays that could be used consistently for long periods of time without any issue. But there are nasal decongestant sprays. So things like Afrin that can be addictive and should not be used for More than a week, so three days, you should be fine. However, any longer than a week, you can develop something called rhinitis Medica Mentosa. So, basically, nasal decongestant sprays are so good at calming down the swollen blood vessels in your nasal passages that when you stop using it, they swell right back up again. 7367064289489784097.voice_to_text: uh first and foremost public service announcement don't get a dog like uh I think this is genuinely quite an important thing to consider if you're thinking of getting a dog are you happy to still walk your dog a couple of times a day even if it's raining all day everyday like it has been for weeks? actually it's quite interesting to think about why do we actually have pets in the first place? it seems like it has a really obvious answer to that question actually a a pet is a huge investment of your own resources uh of time and effort and money uh and anyone interested in this this book is well worth reading it's excellent it's called The Animals Among Us uh and it's by John Bradshaw who is an anthrozoologist  so he studies the relationship between humans and animals undoubtedly there were a huge benefits of having a pet in your life  you know of the companionship and the joy that they bring you and an unconditional love probably sums it up um but there's also yeah there are some positive effects on your mental health how your dog does force you to get out and exercise uh obviously there are service dogs assistance dogs that help people in a very direct way I think it's interesting that in the last 10 years pet ownership has been increasing alongside life possibly becoming more complicated and busy for a lot of people uh and I think this book sort of one of the um main reasons it suggest we have pets is that we are evolutionarily pre programmed to want to be around animals and with people increasingly living in cities and being more detached from nature having a pet in your life sort of fulfills the instinct to be around animals so it's really interesting um why do you have a pet it’s an interesting question

7366952740938845473.voice_to_text: if your resume is getting auto rejected it means you're not getting past the ATS scanners and AI not true the ATS does not scan your CV the ATS does not determine whether you are suitable for the role or not based purely on your CV if you do get auto rejected that's because you have answered questions as part of their application form which is then determined whether you get rejected or pass through to a recruiter to review your CV so for example if one of the requirements for the role is that you need a full driving license if you answer the question that says do you have a full driving license and you say no then you will get auto rejected the ATS does not reject you based on your CV alone and normally the people that are telling you that ATS is will auto reject your CV usually the people are trying to sell you at ATS friendly CVS CV template CV writing services or access to platforms that will score your CV the ATS does not auto reject your CV there is no such thing if you do need help with your CV check out the link in my bio there's a completely free CV template that lots of people have downloaded and have told me is helping them get job interviews and if you want some actual real job search advice and not nonsense hit the follow button cheers

their personal or business credit and business credit whatever y'all get what I'm trying to say so the first thing that I would tell someone who filed bankruptcy and their bankruptcy is discharged is to try to dispute that bankruptcy off of your credit report so lenders and companies that you are applying for a credit card or loan for is not gonna know you file bankruptcy if it's not showing on the second thing that you need to do after you get the bankruptcy removed off of your credit is start off with secure credit cards so a secure credit card means that you are going to have to basically secure the credit card by putting up your own funds to open the account and your credit limit is going to be whatever amount you put on the credit card so for example if you open up a secured credit card and you put $500 on the card your limit is going to be $500 so you're gonna have $500 available to spend when you have this credit card open you wanna make sure that you do not charge more than $50 per month on the card because you want the card to be active you want some type of utilization but you don't want to max out the card every month so I noticed that a lot of people make the mistake 7367767805841657120.voice_to_text: ABBA is an acronym consisting of the first letter of the band members’ names: Agnetha, Björn, Benny and Anna-Frid,  while French rock group Darlin’ had their music described by a Melody Maker journalist as “daft punky thrash,” so they called their next project Daft Punk. Joy Division was the name given to the Jewish sex slaves in Nazi concentration camps, and staying on the morbid theme, Leicester group Kasabian was named after Linda Kasabian, Charles Manson's getaway driver. Leonard Skinner was a PE teacher from Jacksonville, Florida who got a group of boys suspended for wearing their hair too long, which was against the rules at the time. That group of boys then went and formed a band and named it after him. The Rolling Stones are named after a Muddy Waters song, Rollin’ Stone, while Röyksopp is the Norwegian for puffball mushroom; although, for some reason, they changed the Norwegian ø for a Swedish one with umlaut and all. Spandau was a prison in Berlin where Nazis were hanged. When people are being hanged and they're just about to die, they do a jerky movement, and that got nicknamed the Spandau Ballet. Although, the band took the name from graffiti referencing the Spandau Ballet in a nightclub in Germany. UB40 was the name of the attendance card given to people claiming unemployment benefit in the UK, while front man Rivers Cuomo doesn't know why, but as a toddler, his dad gave him the nickname Weezer.

7367068667407830315.video_description: What happens during onboarding can be make or break! As a CEO, I have received a lot of feedback about onboarding, and I’m proud to say that I’ve heard from many people that Clockwork's the best process they’ve been through in starting in a new company. A lot of that is in large part due to the leadership team here who is always thinking about ways to improve that process because it can be so overwhelming.  So, how do we do it? Here are 3 things I think are important to our onboarding process: 1️⃣🗓 We schedule everybody out for the first two weeks. So they have one-on-ones with the leadership team, they’re assigned a buddy who they’ll then work with who will show them the ropes. They have a series of conversations, protocols and policies to read, and they have a person that’s advocating for them and helping them navigate their way in this unfamiliar place. 2️⃣🧠 We are in the habit of hiring really smart people. When that happens, you have a lot of people who are used to being the smartest person in the room. I think just realizing that you’re not the only one anymore and settling into the rhythm of a group of people, a team of people, that operate from that place, is a challenge. But I think we work really hard to really wrap our arms around new people and welcome them in. 3️⃣🤝 We have a real commitment to equity and psychological safety, and so we really try to read a person, understand their cues, and ask them directly what they need from us to be most effective in their jobs. Then we have some social activities in those first couple of weeks. #careeradvice #workculture #teambuilding #newemployee #newjob #nancylyons

In Japan, bear paws are the favourite food of many wealthy people because they believe that this dish is a symbol of power. When cooking it, the chef will first boil the bear paw with onions and ginger. This process can help to remove its fishy flavor. When the bear paw is cooked, it will be cleaned with water and then carefully remove the hairs on the surface of the paw. When cleaning the hairs, the chef need to be very careful. Not only do they have to be in perfect shape, but also to clean the hairs. If too much force is applied, the shape of the paw will be broken. This needs a lot of patience. Once the nails and fur of the paw are clean, the chef will start to make the broth. The main ingredients used are pig bones and chicken claws, as well as onions, ginger, and other seasonings. While waiting for the broth to simmer, the bear's paw needs to be inspected again to make sure the hairs are cleaned out. 7359672942608895274.voice_to_text: Japanese categorizes nouns in 500+ different ways. Similar to how Spanish divides nouns into feminine and masculine, Japanese splits items into their own categories. Unlike Spanish, however, Japanese does not consider these categories as grammatical gender. Instead, they are a part of a system called counterwords, which are a specific way of counting items depending on their category. For instance, if you know the numbers in Japanese, then you know that they are each ni sashi go rokushi t hatsuki do. So what if you were at a Japanese restaurant and wanted to order two of the same thing? You might think that you can just say ni could I say? But this is incorrect. If you want to count actual things, you need to use a whole different set of numbers, which are as follows itotsu, itatsu, mitsu, iotsu, itsutsu, mutsu, nanatsu, yatsu, coconutsu, and Toh. So in a restaurant you'd actually say something like Huttatsu Kurasai. Okay, so what if you wanted to count the amount of bottles on a counter? Well, you could just use the same thing as before, Huttatsu, Huttatsu, etc. it would sound much more natural if you used a different counterword, which is specifically or long thin objects, which is Hong. So you count the bottles by saying Eek horn, ni horn, sam Bon, Yong horn, go horn, drop horn, Nana horn, hatsy horn, q horn, jup horn. There are way more kind of words than just the two that I just Gave. For example, there's a counterword for counting animals there. On the smaller side, Kiki. Then there's a counterword for big animals like elephants. Pole. There's also one for machines, people, cans, volumes of books, and so many more. The method for her execution was beheading, and it did not go smoothly. The executioner messed up his first swing of the axe and lodged it into the back of Mary's head, which she survived. 7343309839432551722.video_description: Title: "Bishop Patrick Wooden Sr. Speaks Out Against Excessive LGBTQ+ Celebrations: A Stand for Faith and Conviction" In a recent address, Bishop Patrick Wooden Sr. of the Upper Room COGIC has raised poignant concerns regarding the proliferation of LGBTQ+ celebrations and awareness days. He has highlighted the multitude of specific days and months dedicated to this lifestyle, questioning the necessity of such extensive observances and labeling the lifestyle as an abomination according to the Bible. Bishop Wooden's passionate stance against what he perceives as an aggressive promotion of LGBTQ+ views onto society underscores his unwavering commitment to his faith and beliefs. He voices concern over the forceful imposition of these celebrations, emphasizing that as believers, they will not passively accept it. In his powerful message, Bishop Wooden asserts, "Do you see how wicked this is? They are trying to ram this stuff down our throats, and as believers, we are not going to allow them to do that." His resolute stand reflects a deep-rooted conviction in upholding the teachings of the Bible and resisting what he views as a cultural shift contrary to his religious beliefs. In a world where diverse perspectives coexist, Bishop Wooden's outspoken views serve as a reminder of the importance of standing firm in one's faith and convictions. While sparking debate and controversy, his message underscores the significance of staying true to one's beliefs in the face of societal pressures and trends. As we navigate discussions around LGBTQ+ rights and celebrations, Bishop Wooden's words provoke reflection on the balance between tolerance, acceptance, and the preservation of individual beliefs. His unwavering stance calls for a respectful dialogue that acknowledges differing viewpoints while upholding the values that hold significance for each individual. In a society where diversity and inclusivity are celebrated, Bishop Wooden's voice serves as a reminder of the importance of respecting differing perspectives while staying true to one's principles. His message challenges us to engage in thoughtful discourse and understanding, even amidst differing viewpoints and beliefs. #BishopPatrickWoodenSr #LGBTQ + #Faith #Conviction #Beliefs #ReligiousFreedom #StandStrong #RespectfulDialogue #Diversity #Inclusivity #Values #Tolerance #Awareness #Celebrations #Controversy #Society #Believer #BibleTeachings #UnwaveringFaith #CultureShift
